forms of CT imaging with contrast has the highest average radiation dosage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT head","CT coronary angiogram","CT chest","CT neck","CT colonography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECT scans generally deliver higher radiation doses compared to other imaging modalities like X-rays and MRI. X-rays involve lower radiation exposure, while MRI does not use ionising radiation at all. In general, excessive radiation exposure can lead to complications such as tissue damage, increased cancer risk, and radiation sickness. Radiation exposure during pregnancy can increase the risk of developmental abnormalities and cancer in the unborn child. Therefore, it is crucial to minimise unnecessary exposure and use alternative imaging methods when possible. Therefore, when considering imaging options, the potential benefits and risks of radiation exposure should be carefully weighed, especially in younger patients and females.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT coronary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E typically involves a higher radiation dose compared to other types of CT scans, averaging around 12-15 millisieverts (mSv). This is due to the need for multiple images to be taken over a short period to capture the movement of the heart and blood vessels. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EIn contrast, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT head\u003C/strong\u003E generally involves a lower radiation dose, averaging around 2 mSv. A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT neck\u003C/strong\u003E also involves a lower dose, typically around 3-4 mSv. A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest\u003C/strong\u003E involves a moderate dose, averaging around 7 mSv, and a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT colonography\u003C/strong\u003E involves a dose of approximately 6 mSv.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Particular care must be taken in ordering radiologic imaging with radiation exposure in younger patients and females.","CT coronary angiograms typically involve higher radiation doses due to the need for multiple images over a short period."],"references":["Ionising radiation and health: https://www.arpansa.gov.au/understanding-radiation/radiation-sources/more-radiation-sources/ionising-radiation-and-health","Patel PR, De Jesus O. CT Scan. [Updated 2023 Jan 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567796/","Lin EC. Radiation risk from medical imaging. Mayo Clin Proc. 2010 Dec;85(12):1142-6; quiz 1146. doi: 10.4065/mcp.2010.0260. PMID: 21123642; PMCID: PMC2996147.","Harvard Health Publishing. Radiation risk from medical imaging. N.d. Harvard Medical School. Available from: https://www.health.harvard.edu/cancer/radiation-risk-from-medical-imaging","Einstein AJ. Radiation from cardiac imaging tests: questions you should ask. Circulation. 2013 Mar 19;127(11):e495-7. doi: 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.112.146043. PMID: 23509035.","Smith-Bindman R, Lipson J, Marcus R, Kim KP, Mahesh M, Gould R, Berrington de Gonz\u00e1lez A, Miglioretti DL. Radiation dose associated with common computed tomography examinations and the associated lifetime attributable risk of cancer. Arch Intern Med. 2009 Dec 14;169(22):2078-86. doi: 10.1001/archinternmed.2009.427. PMID: 20008690; PMCID: PMC4635397."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11816"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88045"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T22:47:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T22:47:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4421"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105616"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attribu